<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-831-099  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 831 099.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  May 8 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>UK anti-hacking bill goes through to House of Lords.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gold, Steve.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer crimesUnited KingdomLegislationLegal Issues.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>UK ANTI-HACKING BILL GOES THROUGH TO HOUSE OF LORDS LONDON, ENGLAND, 1990 MAY05 (NB) -- A private member's bill on computer misuse has passed its thirdreading in the House of Commons, the lower house of the UK's government.andP;  TheBill will now be discussed in the upper house, the House of Lords, prior toreceiving the Queen's assent, and becoming law in a matter of months.andM;The Computer Misuse Bill, which is supported by the British Government,imposes three classes of penalty on so-called computer hackers.andP;  The offencesrange from basic, with a jail penalty of up to three months in prison, tooffences involving premeditated damage and/or financial gain with a maximumpenalty of five years in prison.andM;During the third reading of the bill, which took place in the House ofCommons last Friday, Mr Micheal Colvin, member of parliament for Romsey andWaterside, the bill's sponsor, said that society's increasing dependency oninformation technology suggested that hacking would become even morewidespread.andM;His bill would discourage such behaviour and ensure that those who defy thelaw will be prosecuted, he said.andM;Mr Douglas Hogg, the UK's Minister for Industry, said: &quot;We do need to beextremely careful about extending the rights of search in respect of the vastmajority of residual cases.&quot;andM;Under current UK legislation, computer hacking (defined as unauthorizedaccess to a computer) as well as the introduction of virus or logic bombprograms to computer systems, is not specifically illegal.andP;  Instead, legalprotection takes the form of a possible prosecution under the Theft Act,although possible penalties are measured in the hundreds of pounds, ratherthan the thousands, which anti-hacking legislation proponents argue isnecessary to act as a deterrent.andM;(Steve Gold/1990505)</TEXT></DOC>